Question 1¶

Describe how you preprocessed the data. Why did you choose that technique?

I did the following pre-processing steps

  1. Mean subtraction: This is the most common and obvious pre-processing step. I took the mean across all the samples of the training data and computed a 'training mean image'. I then subtracted this image from the training, validation and test data. This has the effect of centering the data around the origin (for every dimension of the feature vector) and thus making it more suitable for optimization.
  2. Min max scaling: I initially did not bother with normalization (i.e dividing with standard deviation) because these are 8 bit images (pixel values 0-255). Normalizing typically makes sense if different features are of different scales. But here all the feature values have the same scale (0-255). However I noticed that my model was taking more epochs to converge to the minimum (> 50 epochs). After min max scaling the inputs (min val -1.0 and max val 1.0), I was achieving the same results in about 10 epochs.
  3. Histogram Equalization: From a general look at the training dataset, the images are taken under very varied lighting conditions. Performing a histogram equalization helps to balance the distribution of pixels in an image and thus alleviate the effects of increased or decreased lighting. In practice doing an histogram equalization allowed me to get a 1-2% boost in my final test accuracy result. Please note that I first did the histogram equalization on the raw input pickled data before doing the other pre-processing operations.

Question 2¶

Describe how you set up the training, validation and testing data for your model. Optional: If you generated additional data, how did you generate the data? Why did you generate the data? What are the differences in the new dataset (with generated data) from the original dataset?

Data augmentation:¶

As seen from the histogram, the given dataset is highly unbalanced. For eg., traffic sign 0 (20 km/h) has about 200 occurences while traffic sign 1 (30 km/h) has about 2200 occurences in the training data. I wrote a python script (see attached augment_data.py) to randomly apply affine transformations to the not so well represented images. I decided to choose a threshold value of 600 as the minimum number of images that are expected to be present for any given label.I also decided to clamp the maximum number of images that represent a particular sample to 1250. The idea here is not to terribly over represent any particular label and thereby biasing the conv net towards that label. The affine transformations I applied were randomly chosen values as follows

  1. Rotation:-10 degrees to 10 degrees
  2. Translation: - 6mm to 6mm in x and y directions
  3. Scale: 0.9 to 1.1 zoom factors
  4. Shear: -4 degress to 4 degrees
  5. I also added random Gaussian noise to approximately 1/3 of the augmented images.

Train / Validation/ Testing split:¶

I used the sklearn module to split the training data into 80% training set and 20% validation set. I preserved the given test data as it is.

Note: During initial training, I obtained the biggest boost in my testing accuracy only after data augmentation. My initial testing accuracy hovered around 70-75%. Data augmentation boosted that number to about 91%.

Model Evaluation¶

In [14]:
# model evaluation (on validation data)
batch_size = 500
def evaluate(X_data, y_data, sess):
    num_examples = len(X_data)
    #print("num examples and batch size - must be same", num_examples, batch_size)
    total_accuracy, total_loss = 0, 0
    #sess = tf.get_default_session()
    for offset in range(0, num_examples, batch_size):
        batch_x, batch_y = X_data[offset:offset+batch_size], y_data[offset:offset+batch_size]
        loss, accuracy =  sess.run([loss_operation, accuracy_operation], feed_dict={X_tf: batch_x, y_tf: batch_y,\
                                                                                    keep_prob: 1.0})
        total_accuracy += (accuracy * batch_x.shape[0])
        total_loss     += (loss * batch_x.shape[0])
    return total_loss / num_examples, total_accuracy / num_examples

Question 3 _What does your final architecture look like? (Type of model, layers, sizes, connectivity, etc.)

I used an improvised leNet5 model in my final architecture. I started with the basic leNet5 model as described in the lectures and slowly improvised it over different trials. The main differences bwtween my final model and the leNet5 model is I have an additional convolutional layer, less pooling layers and more neurons in the hidden layer. I have described my architecture in detail below

My final architecture looks as follows

  1. Input: Preprocessed and augmented color images of size 32 x 32 x 3

  2. Conv layer 1: Kernel size 5 x 5 mapping 3 channels to 32 filter outputs. Strides of 1 x 1. Relu activation. Dropout 0.35.

  3. Max pool layer 1: Kernel size 2x2 and strides of 2 x 2.

  4. Batch normalization.

  5. Conv layer 2: Kernel size 5 x 5 mapping 32 inputs to 64 filter outputs. Strides of 1 x 1. Relu activation. Dropout 0.35.

  6. No max pool.

  7. Batch normalization.

  8. Conv layer 3: Kernel size 5 x 5 mapping 64 inputs to 128 filter outputs. Strides of 1 x 1. Relu activation. Dropout 0.35.

  9. No max pool

  10. Batch normalization.

  11. FC layer 1: 1024 hidden neurons. Relu activation. Dropout 0.35.

  12. Batch normalization.

  13. FC layer 2: 1024 hidden neurons. Relu activation. Dropout 0.35.

  14. Batch normalization.

  15. Final FC layer: 43 neurons.

Question 4¶

How did you train your model? (Type of optimizer, batch size, epochs, hyperparameters, etc.)

  1. Optimizer: I trained my model using the adam optimizer (like in the lenet lab). The default training rates of 0.001 seemed to work pretty good. Decreasing the learning rate (to 0.0001) resulted in way more epochs and not any significant bump in accuracy. Also adam optimizer provides this nice option of automatically decreasing the learning rate with increasing epochs.
  2. Batch size: I tried batch sizes of 100, 250 and 500. This did not seem to have much of an impact on the final results. So I decided to stick with 500 (500 was the maximum I could fit in my RAM).
  3. Weights initialization: I started by choosing weights randomly from a normal distribution (mean = 0 and std = 1.0). After several trials I realized my model was not happy with these weights. My model failed to converge and I was stuck at validation accuracies around 7%. I started reducing the variance and the model seemed to be happy with this. I learnt that initializing with large values for weights ends up biasing the model. It was better to sample from a random normal distribution with mean 0.0 and std around 0.05 or less. I then switched over to using the tensor flow Xavier initialization scheme. This has the nice property of scaling down the weights (picked from a random normal distribution) according to the number of layers and number of neurons in the network.
  4. Regularization: I tried to apply L2 regularization. This did not help my model achieve better results by avoiding overfitting. My suspicion is that the xavier weight initialization scheme that I use inherently performs some kind of weight scaling for every iteration. So it is possible that doing a L2 regularization on top of that was not really helpful
  5. Dropouts: Dropouts played quite an effective role in preventing my model from overfitting a lot. My test accuracies improved by 1-2% after using a keep probability of 0.5. Reducing the keep probability to 0.35 further improved the test accuracy by 1% or so.
  6. Batch normalization: This was not covered in the course material. Batch normalization performs a normalization of the computed outputs of each layer (except the final fc layer) before these outputs are fed into the next layer. This helps to keep the values of weights and features small throughout the model and thus making the optimizer happy I used the inbuilt tensor flow routine for performing batch normalization. Performing batch normalization helped me quite a bit in reducing the number of epochs while also potentially providing a slight bump in my test accuracies.
  7. Max pool: As I increased the number of layers in my model, I realized max pool was not helping me. This makes sense since pooling shrinks your images and more the layers the smaller and less significant is your input. I performed max pooling for just the first convolutional layer (out of 3 convolutional layers) in my final model.

Please note: I intentionally did not perform hyper parameter training for 2 reasons

  1. I was limited by the hardware choices at my disposal.
  2. Individually playing with different parameters allowed me to gain a deeper understanding of my model and deep learning in general.

Question 5¶

What approach did you take in coming up with a solution to this problem? It may have been a process of trial and error, in which case, outline the steps you took to get to the final solution and why you chose those steps. Perhaps your solution involved an already well known implementation or architecture. In this case, discuss why you think this is suitable for the current problem.

I started with the leNet architecture as shown in the lessons and slowly started improvising on it. Please look at the attached document (TrafficSignsResults.pdf) where I have documented my different trials and accuracies.

Some general observations / lessons learnt

  1. Initializing the weights correctly is expremely important. The weight scale parameter (if you are not using Xavier initialization or some similar automated weight scaler) is probably as important a hyper parameter as the learning rate for the optimizer.
  2. Data augmentation provided the biggest boost in my test accuracies. I believe I could explore some smarter strategies to perform data augmentation to achieve even higher test accuracies than the 95% currently attained by my model.
  3. Dropouts were highly effective in preventing overfitting.
  4. It generally helps to keep the values of your features (and weights) small. Optimizers in general do not seem to like large values. So scaling down the inputs is quite important. Also batch normalization is your friend especially if you have a very big network with lots of layers.
  5. My test accuracies were consistently 4-6% lower than my validation accuracies. This troubled me a lot. This cannot be attributed to overfitting. I took great care in ensuring that my validation set is quite 'pristine'. I used it only to print out the accuracies during training. I never used it for hyper parameter training either. My final conclusion on this is that the distribution of labels in the given train data set (and I maintain the same distribution for my validation set) is quite different from the distribution of the test data set (which I verified by plotting the distributions of the train and test datasets). One could easily overcome this by changing the distribution of the validation set to match the test set. But that would be cheating since in real world scenarios one would never be given the test labels.

Question 6¶

Choose five candidate images of traffic signs and provide them in the report. Are there any particular qualities of the image(s) that might make classification difficult? It could be helpful to plot the images in the notebook.

I will choose 5 candidate signs based on the above classification report

  1. 2 best performing candidates - 13 (Yield), 35 (Ahead only)
  2. 1 average performing candidate - 5 (Speed limit 80 km/h)
  3. 2 worst performing candidates - 27 (Pedestrians), 20 (Dangerous curve to right)

Potential reasons why the model might find it easy or diffcult to classify the candidate images (please scroll down for visualization below

  1. Candidate 13 and 35 - These are images that have a well defined shape (triangle for 'yield' sign) and sharp lines (arrow for 'ahead only'). Neural networks quickly tend to converge upon edges and boundaries in the very first layer and converge upon well defined shapes (triangles, circles etc) in the second or third layer. So these candidate images should be relatively easy for classification
  2. Candidate 5 - This image adds an additional layer of difficulty in that the network has to succesfully distinguish the numbers in the sign (80 km/h). This goes beyond just simply detecting lines and shapes.
  3. Candidates 27 and 20 - These candidates go beyond lines, shapes or numbers. The model should be able to detect the picture of human in the 'pedestrian' sign. This makes it challenging because the picture of a human may not necessarily be the same in all the signs. In addition there are other signs (eg. children crossing) that have pictures of humans too. The last sign ('Dangerous curve to the right') simply has a tiny curve in the center. This seemingly simple thing might still be very hard because such curves are pretty much present in most other traffic signs. So the model has to reason out that an isolated tiny curve by itself represents candidate 20.

from scipy import misc
def preprocess_test_image(img):
    img = np.reshape(img, [1,32,32,3])
    img = preprocess.hist_eq(img)
    img = preprocess.subtract_mean(img.astype(np.float32), mean_img)
    img = preprocess.min_max_scaling(img, train_min, train_max)
    return img

Question 8¶

Use the model's softmax probabilities to visualize the certainty of its predictions, tf.nn.top_k could prove helpful here. Which predictions is the model certain of? Uncertain? If the model was incorrect in its initial prediction, does the correct prediction appear in the top k? (k should be 5 at most)

In [25]:
smax_prob_op = tf.nn.softmax(logits)
cnt = 0;
for i in img_list:
    s_prob = sess.run(smax_prob_op, feed_dict = {X_tf: i, keep_prob: 1.0})
    top_5_prob, top_5_idx = sess.run(tf.nn.top_k(tf.constant(s_prob), k=5))
    lbl_names = [sign_names[str(i)] for i in top_5_idx[0,:]]
    with plt.style.context('seaborn-notebook'):
        plt.figure()
        ax = plt.subplot(1,2,1)
        plt.imshow(sample_imgs[cnt])
        plt.title(sign_names[str(candidate_labels[cnt])])
        #plt.tight_layout
    with plt.style.context('ggplot'):           
        ax = plt.subplot(1,2,2)
        plt.barh(range(5), top_5_prob[0,:], align = 'center')
        plt.yticks(range(5), lbl_names)
        plt.xticks(rotation = 'vertical')
        plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
        plt.tight_layout()
        cnt += 1

Some observations:

  1. The above visualizations got me surprised as well. While my model missed predicting the signs for which it supposedly had a high confidence based on the test data F1 scores ('yield' and 'ahead only'), it also got it wrong with a very high softmax probability (about 0.9)! Similarly the correctly predicted images for the worst performing candidates ('Pedestrians' and 'sharp right curve') got low softmax probability scores (about 0.4). I do not yet have a satisfying answer for this.
  2. On closer inspection, the distorted 'yield sign' that I downloaded from the internet does look like a giant left arrow. This probably made the model think it is a 'keep left' sign. Also the 'ahead only' sign got classified as 'go straight or right', which is not too bad. So it is heartening to know that the model is able to make 'intelligent' guesses.
  3. It seems like the model does perform really well for well centered un-distorted images while it has troubles with distorted images. This is probably not too big a deal since the real world images (probably captured from a camera mounted on a car) will not be as highly distorted as the test images I downloaded from the internet.
  4. Another way the above issue can be addressed is through data augmentation. While I already apply some distortions in my augmented data, it is probably not high enough. In addition I did not distort images which already had high enough representation in the training data (the 'Yield' and 'Go Ahead' signs had more than 650 samples. So they were not augmented with affine transformations).
  5. If I were asked to do one thing that would improve the model's performance even further, that would be data augmentation. Definitely smarter augmentation can boost the performance of this model. However I believe data augmentation will be a big part of the upcoming project. So I will rest this project for now.
